                        "speaker": null,
                        "text_blocks": [
                            {
                                "start": 0,
                                "stop": 10.258,
                                "byte_start": 28672,
                                "byte_stop": 69736,
                                "text": "The opinion of the Court in No. 95-1726, United States against LaBonte, will be announced by Justice Thomas."
                            }
                        ]
                    },
                    {
                        "start": 10.258,
                        "stop": 234.997,
                        "byte_start": 69736,
                        "byte_stop": 968558,
                        "speaker": null,
                        "text_blocks": [
                            {
                                "start": 10.258,
                                "stop": 16.724,
                                "byte_start": 69736,
                                "byte_stop": 95650,
                                "text": "This case comes to us on a writ of certiorari to the Court of Appeals for the First Circuit."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 16.724,
                                "stop": 30.705,
                                "byte_start": 95650,
                                "byte_stop": 151552,
                                "text": "At the bottom, this case involves what to -- how do you sentence an individual who has committed one or two crimes but not a series of crimes under the federal statute."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 30.705,
                                "stop": 56.286,
                                "byte_start": 151552,
                                "byte_stop": 253848,
                                "text": "The Title 28 U.S.C. Section 994(h) directs the United States Sentencing Commission to \u201cassure\u201d that its sentencing guidelines specify a prison sentence \u0022at or near the maximum term authorized for categories of\u0022 adult offenders who commit their third felony drug offense or third violent crime."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 56.286,
                                "stop": 61.664,
                                "byte_start": 253848,
                                "byte_stop": 275372,
                                "text": "The Commission sought to implement this directive in its Career Offender Guideline."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 61.664,
                                "stop": 83.915,
                                "byte_start": 275372,
                                "byte_stop": 364398,
                                "text": "That Guideline initially failed to designate which \u0022maximum term\u0022 a sentencing court was to use when federal law establishes a basic statutory maximum for persons convicted of a particular offense, but also provides an enhanced penalty -- penalty for career offenders convicted of that same offense."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 83.915,
                                "stop": 100.551,
                                "byte_start": 364398,
                                "byte_stop": 430958,
                                "text": "In this case, the District Court used such an enhancement in sentencing the respondents, each of whom was convicted of a federal -- or of federal drug felonies and qualified as a career offender under the Career Offender Guideline."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 100.551,
                                "stop": 116.73,
                                "byte_start": 430958,
                                "byte_stop": 495637,
                                "text": "After the First Circuit affirmed the convictions and sentences, the Commission adopted Amendment 506, which altered the Career Offender Guideline\u0027s commentary to preclude consideration of the statutory sentence enhancements."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 116.73,
                                "stop": 136.292,
                                "byte_start": 495637,
                                "byte_stop": 573900,
                                "text": "One District Judge found that the -- that Amendment 506 was contrary to Section 994(h) and refused to reduce the sentences of respondents Dyer and Hunnewell, but another judge of the same court upheld the amendment and reduced respondent LaBonte\u0027s sentence."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 136.292,
                                "stop": 149.841,
                                "byte_start": 573900,
                                "byte_stop": 628130,
                                "text": "The First Circuit consolidated the ensuing appeals and held that the Career Offender Guideline, as construed under Amendment 506, was a reasonable implementation of Section 994(h)\u0027s directive."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 149.841,
                                "stop": 153.446,
                                "byte_start": 628130,
                                "byte_stop": 642550,
                                "text": "In an opinion filed with the clerk today, we reversed."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 153.446,
                                "stop": 160.789,
                                "byte_start": 642550,
                                "byte_stop": 671911,
                                "text": "Amendment 506 is inconsistent with Section 994(h)\u0027s plain and unambiguous language."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 160.789,
                                "stop": 177.323,
                                "byte_start": 671911,
                                "byte_stop": 738053,
                                "text": "Assuming that Congress said what it meant in drafting Section 994(h), and giving the words used their \u201cordinary meaning,\u201d the phrase \u201cmaximum term authorized\u201d must be read to include all applicable statutory sentencing enhancements."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 177.323,
                                "stop": 190.658,
                                "byte_start": 738053,
                                "byte_stop": 791343,
                                "text": "Respondents\u0027 contrary argument that the phrase refers only to the highest penalty authorized by the offense of conviction, excluding any enhancements, has no support in the text of the statute."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 190.658,
                                "stop": 199.948,
                                "byte_start": 791343,
                                "byte_stop": 828541,
                                "text": "Their assertion that Section 994(h) is ambiguous is based on a strained construction of the phrase \u201ccategories of defendants.\u201d"
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 199.948,
                                "stop": 207.856,
                                "byte_start": 828541,
                                "byte_stop": 860097,
                                "text": "Similarly, we find no ambiguity in the phrase \u201cat or near\u201d the maximum sentence authorized."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 207.856,
                                "stop": 217.224,
                                "byte_start": 860097,
                                "byte_stop": 897609,
                                "text": "Although the phrase \u201cat or near\u201d unquestionably permits a certain degree of flexibility for upward and downward departure and adjustments."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 217.224,
                                "stop": 227.25,
                                "byte_start": 897609,
                                "byte_stop": 937733,
                                "text": "It does not license the Commission to select as the relevant maximum term a sentence that is different from the congressionally authorized maximum term."
                            },
                            {
                                "start": 227.25,
                                "stop": 234.997,
                                "byte_start": 937733,
                                "byte_stop": 968558,
                                "text": "Justice Breyer has filed a dissenting opinion, in which Justices Stevens and Ginsburg have joined."
                            }
                        ]
                    }
                ]
            }
        ]
    },
